The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Centre declares nationwide alert

 OUR BUREAU

 July 11: The Centre has asked all the state governments to put their security apparatus on high alert following the serial blasts that rocked Mumbai this evening. A red alert has been sounded in Delhi.

 The nationwide alert was declared after home minister Shivraj Patil met Prime Minister Manmohan Singh around 8 pm. Patil had earlier briefed UPA chairperson Sonia Gandhi about the explosions.

 Sonia is travelling to Mumbai along with Patil and railway minister Lalu Prasad tonight to take stock of the situation. Home secretary V.K. Duggal would also accompany them.

 Duggal has discussed security measures with the Maharashtra home secretary and the director-general of police.

 Police said security had been beefed up in Delhi and barricades had come up at several places.

 In Calcutta, the police sounded a red alert. Deputy commissioner (headquarters) P.K. Chatterjee said all the police stations across the city were put on red alert as soon as news of the blasts came in. Officers-in-charge of police stations have been asked to keep round-the-clock surveillance in sensitive areas. 

 The Special Branch, the city polices intelligence wing, has been instructed to keep close watch on vital installations like Writers Buildings, Raj Bhavan and the American Center. 

 City police chief Prasun Mukherjee held an emergency meeting with senior officers this evening at Lalbazar. Mukherjee later said security has been tightened across the city.

 Security agencies in Punjab and Haryana are also on high alert. Police said security agencies in the two states and Chandigarh have been asked to keep watch on railway stations, bus stands and crowded market-places.

 In Tamil Nadu, chief minister M. Karunanidhi has asked the director-general of police to tighten security at all key public places, vital installations and important places of worship across the state.

 The serial blasts came on a day the Tamil Nadu police seized as many as 86 bags of a variety of country-made bombs from a lorry in a crowded market area in north Chennai. 




